How the code works:

This system connects to your home Wi-Fi to automatically get the exact time from the internet, meaning you never have to set the clock manually.
It saves this time onto a small backup battery clock module, so even if your Wi-Fi goes down or the power cuts out, the system keeps counting the time perfectly 
and will not lose its place.

The website built into the board is protected by two different passwords.
The first password lets anyone log in to see the countdown timers and turn the pumps on manually if needed.
The second password unlocks a special section at the bottom of the page that shows the system health, such as how long the board has been running,
the Wi-Fi signal strength, and if the water tank is running empty.

Thanks to an internal memory, the system always remembers the last time it watered the plants. 
If the power cuts out and turns back on, it checks this memory so it knows exactly when to start again without accidentally watering your plants twice.
Pump 1 is set to run automatically every two days at 8:00 AM, and Pump 2 runs once a week on Saturdays at 8:02 AM. T
here is also a built-in safety feature for a water float sensor, which automatically stops the pumps from running if the main water tank goes completely empty.

How to set it up:

First, open the code in the Arduino IDE and type your Wi-Fi name and password at lines 9 and 10.
Then, change the website passwords on lines 13 and 14 to whatever you prefer.

If you live outside of Italy or Central Europe, you can change the time zone setting on line 18 to match your area. 
Finally, upload the code to your board and open the Serial Monitor at 115200 speed to see the website address you need to type into your phone or computer browser.
